# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: point-cloud-processing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A **3D scanner** can be based on many different technologies, each with its own limitations, advantages and costs.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Many limitations in the kind of objects that can be digitized are still present.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] For example, optical technology may encounter difficulties with dark, shiny, reflective or transparent objects while industrial computed tomography scanning, structured-light 3D scanners, LiDAR and Time-Of-Flight 3D scanners can be used to construct digital 3D models, without destructive testing.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Collected 3D data is useful for a wide variety of applications.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These devices are used extensively by the entertainment industry in the production of movies and video games, including virtual reality.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Other common applications of this technology include augmented reality, motion capture, gesture recognition, robotic mapping, industrial design, orthotics and prosthetics, reverse engineering and prototyping, quality control/inspection and the digitization of cultural artifacts.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The purpose of a 3D scanner is usually to create a 3D model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This 3D model consists of a polygon mesh or point cloud of geometric samples on the surface of the subject.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These points can then be used to extrapolate the shape of the subject (a process called reconstruction).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] If color information is collected at each point, then the colors and textures on the surface of the subject can also be determined.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 3D scanners share several traits with cameras.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Like most cameras, they have a cone-like field of view, and like cameras, they can only collect information about surfaces that are not obscured.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] While a camera collects color information about surfaces within its field of view, a 3D scanner collects distance information about surfaces within its field of view.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The "picture" produced by a 3D scanner describes the distance to a surface at each point in the picture.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This allows the three dimensional position of each point in the picture to be identified.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In some situations, a single scan will not produce a complete model of the subject.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Multiple scans, from different directions are usually helpful to obtain information about all sides of the subject.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These scans have to be brought into a common reference system, a process that is usually called *alignment* or *registration*, and then merged to create a complete 3D model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This whole process, going from the single range map to the whole model, is usually known as the 3D scanning pipeline.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] There are a variety of technologies for digitally acquiring the shape of a 3D object.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The techniques work with most or all sensor types including optical, acoustic, laser scanning, radar, thermal, and seismic.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 3D scan technologies can be split in 2 categories: contact and non-contact.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Non-contact solutions can be further divided into two main categories, active and passive.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] There are a variety of technologies that fall under each of these categories.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Contact 3D scanners work by physically probing (touching) the part and recording the position of the sensor as the probe moves around the part.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Both modern CMMs and Articulated Arms can also be fitted with non-contact laser scanners instead of touch probes.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Active scanners emit some kind of radiation or light and detect its reflection or radiation passing through object in order to probe an object or environment.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Possible types of emissions used include light, ultrasound or x-ray.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The time-of-flight 3D laser scanner is an active scanner that uses laser light to probe the subject.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] At the heart of this type of scanner is a time-of-flight laser range finder.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The laser range finder finds the distance of a surface by timing the round-trip time of a pulse of light.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A laser is used to emit a pulse of light and the amount of time before the reflected light is seen by a detector is measured.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Since the speed of light c is known, the round-trip time determines the travel distance of the light, which is twice the distance between the scanner and the surface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] If t is the round-trip time, then distance is equal to $\textstyle c\!\cdot \!t/2$ .
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The accuracy of a time-of-flight 3D laser scanner depends on how precisely we can measure the t time: 3.3 picoseconds (approx.) is the time taken for light to travel 1 millimetre.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The laser range finder only detects the distance of one point in its direction of view.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Thus, the scanner scans its entire field of view one point at a time by changing the range finder's direction of view to scan different points.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The view direction of the laser range finder can be changed either by rotating the range finder itself, or by using a system of rotating mirrors.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The latter method is commonly used because mirrors are much lighter and can thus be rotated much faster and with greater accuracy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Typical time-of-flight 3D laser scanners can measure the distance of 10,000-100,000 points every second.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight devices are also available in a 2D configuration.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This is referred to as a time-of-flight camera.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Triangulation based 3D laser scanners are also active scanners that use laser light to probe the environment.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] With respect to time-of-flight 3D laser scanner the triangulation laser shines a laser on the subject and exploits a camera to look for the location of the laser dot.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Depending on how far away the laser strikes a surface, the laser dot appears at different places in the camera's field of view.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This technique is called triangulation because the laser dot, the camera and the laser emitter form a triangle.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The length of one side of the triangle, the distance between the camera and the laser emitter is known.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The angle of the laser emitter corner is also known.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The angle of the camera corner can be determined by looking at the location of the laser dot in the camera's field of view.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These three pieces of information fully determine the shape and size of the triangle and give the location of the laser dot corner of the triangle.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In most cases a laser stripe, instead of a single laser dot, is swept across the object to speed up the acquisition process.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The use of triangulation to measure distances dates to antiquity.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight range finders are capable of operating over long distances on the order of kilometres.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These scanners are thus suitable for scanning large structures like buildings or geographic features.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A disadvantage is that, due to the high speed of light, measuring the round-trip time is difficult and so the accuracy of the distance measurement is relatively low, on the order of millimetres.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Triangulation range finders, on the other hand, have a range of usually limited to a few meters for reasonably sized devices, but their accuracy is relatively high.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The accuracy of triangulation range finders is on the order of tens of micrometers.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Time-of-flight scanners' accuracy can be lost when the laser hits the edge of an object because the information that is sent back to the scanner is from two different locations for one laser pulse.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The coordinate relative to the scanner's position for a point that has hit the edge of an object will be calculated based on an average and therefore will put the point in the wrong place.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] When using a high resolution scan on an object the chances of the beam hitting an edge are increased and the resulting data will show noise just behind the edges of the object.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Scanners with a smaller beam width will help to solve this problem but will be limited by range as the beam width will increase over distance.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Software can also help by determining that the first object to be hit by the laser beam should cancel out the second.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] At a rate of 10,000 sample points per second, low resolution scans can take less than a second, but high resolution scans, requiring millions of samples, can take minutes for some time-of-flight scanners.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The problem this creates is distortion from motion.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Since each point is sampled at a different time, any motion in the subject or the scanner will distort the collected data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Thus, it is usually necessary to mount both the subject and the scanner on stable platforms and minimise vibration.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Using these scanners to scan objects in motion is very difficult.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Recently, there has been research on compensating for distortion from small amounts of vibration and distortions due to motion and/or rotation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Short-range laser scanners can not usually encompass a depth of field more than 1 meter.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] When scanning in one position for any length of time slight movement can occur in the scanner position due to changes in temperature.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] If the scanner is set on a tripod and there is strong sunlight on one side of the scanner then that side of the tripod will expand and slowly distort the scan data from one side to another.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Some laser scanners have level compensators built into them to counteract any movement of the scanner during the scan process.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In a conoscopic system, a laser beam is projected onto the surface and then the immediate reflection along the same ray-path are put through a conoscopic crystal and projected onto a CCD.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The result is a diffraction pattern, that can be frequency analyzed to determine the distance to the measured surface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The main advantage with conoscopic holography is that only a single ray-path is needed for measuring, thus giving an opportunity to measure for instance the depth of a finely drilled hole.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Hand-held laser scanners create a 3D image through the triangulation mechanism described above: a laser dot or line is projected onto an object from a hand-held device and a sensor (typically a charge-coupled device or position sensitive device) measures the distance to the surface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Data is collected in relation to an internal coordinate system and therefore to collect data where the scanner is in motion the position of the scanner must be determined.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The position can be determined by the scanner using reference features on the surface being scanned (typically adhesive reflective tabs, but natural features have been also used in research work) or by using an external tracking method.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] External tracking often takes the form of a laser tracker (to provide the sensor position) with integrated camera (to determine the orientation of the scanner) or a photogrammetric solution using 3 or more cameras providing the complete six degrees of freedom of the scanner.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Both techniques tend to use infrared light-emitting diodes attached to the scanner which are seen by the camera(s) through filters providing resilience to ambient lighting.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Data is collected by a computer and recorded as data points within three-dimensional space, with processing this can be converted into a triangulated mesh and then a computer-aided design model, often as non-uniform rational B-spline surfaces.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Hand-held laser scanners can combine this data with passive, visible-light sensors — which capture surface textures and colors — to build (or "reverse engineer") a full 3D model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Structured-light 3D scanners project a pattern of light on the subject and look at the deformation of the pattern on the subject.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The pattern is projected onto the subject using either an LCD projector or other stable light source.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A camera, offset slightly from the pattern projector, looks at the shape of the pattern and calculates the distance of every point in the field of view.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Structured-light scanning is still a very active area of research with many research papers published each year.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Perfect maps have also been proven useful as structured light patterns that solve the correspondence problem and allow for error detection and error correction.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The advantage of structured-light 3D scanners is speed and precision.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Instead of scanning one point at a time, structured light scanners scan multiple points or the entire field of view at once.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Scanning an entire field of view in a fraction of a second reduces or eliminates the problem of distortion from motion.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Some existing systems are capable of scanning moving objects in real-time.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A real-time scanner using digital fringe projection and phase-shifting technique (certain kinds of structured light methods) was developed, to capture, reconstruct, and render high-density details of dynamically deformable objects (such as facial expressions) at 40 frames per second.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Recently, another scanner has been developed.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Different patterns can be applied to this system, and the frame rate for capturing and data processing achieves 120 frames per second.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] It can also scan isolated surfaces, for example two moving hands.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] By utilising the binary defocusing technique, speed breakthroughs have been made that could reach hundreds to thousands of frames per second.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Modulated light 3D scanners shine a continually changing light at the subject.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Usually the light source simply cycles its amplitude in a sinusoidal pattern.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A camera detects the reflected light and the amount the pattern is shifted by determines the distance the light travelled.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Modulated light also allows the scanner to ignore light from sources other than a laser, so there is no interference.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These techniques produce a discrete 3D volumetric representation that can be directly visualised, manipulated or converted to traditional 3D surface by mean of isosurface extraction algorithms.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Passive 3D imaging solutions do not emit any kind of radiation themselves, but instead rely on detecting reflected ambient radiation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Most solutions of this type detect visible light because it is a readily available ambient radiation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Other types of radiation, such as infrared could also be used.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Passive methods can be very cheap, because in most cases they do not need particular hardware but simple digital cameras.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Photogrammetry provides reliable information about 3D shapes of physical objects based on analysis of photographic images.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The resulting 3D data is typically provided as a 3D point cloud, 3D mesh or 3D points.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Various software packages are available including PhotoModeler, Geodetic Systems, Autodesk ReCap, RealityCapture and Agisoft Metashape (see comparison of photogrammetry software).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Semi-automatic building extraction from lidar data and high-resolution images is also a possibility.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Again, this approach allows modelling without physically moving towards the location or object.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] From airborne lidar data, digital surface model (DSM) can be generated and then the objects higher than the ground are automatically detected from the DSM.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Based on general knowledge about buildings, geometric characteristics such as size, height and shape information are then used to separate the buildings from other objects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The extracted building outlines are then simplified using an orthogonal algorithm to obtain better cartographic quality.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Watershed analysis can be conducted to extract the ridgelines of building roofs.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The ridgelines as well as slope information are used to classify the buildings per type.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The buildings are then reconstructed using three parametric building models (flat, gabled, hipped).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Lidar and other terrestrial laser scanning technology offers the fastest, automated way to collect height or distance information. lidar or laser for height measurement of buildings is becoming very promising.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Commercial applications of both airborne lidar and ground laser scanning technology have proven to be fast and accurate methods for building height extraction.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The building extraction task is needed to determine building locations, ground elevation, orientations, building size, rooftop heights, etc.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Most buildings are described to sufficient details in terms of general polyhedra, i.e., their boundaries can be represented by a set of planar surfaces and straight lines.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Further processing such as expressing building footprints as polygons is used for data storing in GIS databases.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Using laser scans and images taken from ground level and a bird's-eye perspective, Fruh and Zakhor present an approach to automatically create textured 3D city models.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This approach involves registering and merging the detailed facade models with a complementary airborne model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The airborne modeling process generates a half-meter resolution model with a bird's-eye view of the entire area, containing terrain profile and building tops.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Ground-based modeling process results in a detailed model of the building facades.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Using the DSM obtained from airborne laser scans, they localize the acquisition vehicle and register the ground-based facades to the airborne model by means of Monte Carlo localization (MCL).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Finally, the two models are merged with different resolutions to obtain a 3D model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Using an airborne laser altimeter, Haala, Brenner and Anders combined height data with the existing ground plans of buildings.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The ground plans of buildings had already been acquired either in analog form by maps and plans or digitally in a 2D GIS.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The project was done in order to enable an automatic data capture by the integration of these different types of information.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Afterwards virtual reality city models are generated in the project by texture processing, e.g. by mapping of terrestrial images.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The project demonstrated the feasibility of rapid acquisition of 3D urban GIS.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Ground plans proved are another very important source of information for 3D building reconstruction.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Compared to results of automatic procedures, these ground plans proved more reliable since they contain aggregated information which has been made explicit by human interpretation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] For this reason, ground plans, can considerably reduce costs in a reconstruction project.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] An example of existing ground plan data usable in building reconstruction is the Digital Cadastral map, which provides information on the distribution of property, including the borders of all agricultural areas and the ground plans of existing buildings.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Additionally information as street names and the usage of buildings (e.g. garage, residential building, office block, industrial building, church) is provided in the form of text symbols.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] At the moment the Digital Cadastral map is built up as a database covering an area, mainly composed by digitizing preexisting maps or plans.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The point clouds produced by 3D scanners and 3D imaging can be used directly for measurement and visualisation in the architecture and construction world.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Most applications, however, use instead polygonal 3D models, NURBS surface models, or editable feature-based CAD models (aka solid models).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These CAD models describe not simply the envelope or shape of the object, but CAD models also embody the "design intent" (i.e., critical features and their relationship to other features).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] An example of design intent not evident in the shape alone might be a brake drum's lug bolts, which must be concentric with the hole in the centre of the drum.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This knowledge would drive the sequence and method of creating the CAD model; a designer with an awareness of this relationship would not design the lug bolts referenced to the outside diameter, but instead, to the center.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A modeler creating a CAD model will want to include both Shape and design intent in the complete CAD model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Vendors offer different approaches to getting to the parametric CAD model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Some export the NURBS surfaces and leave it to the CAD designer to complete the model in CAD (e.g., Geomagic, Imageware, Rhino 3D).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Others use the scan data to create an editable and verifiable feature based model that is imported into CAD with full feature tree intact, yielding a complete, native CAD model, capturing both shape and design intent (e.g.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] For instance, the market offers various plug-ins for established CAD-programs, such as SolidWorks.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Xtract3D, DezignWorks and Geomagic for SolidWorks allow manipulating a 3D scan directly inside SolidWorks.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Still other CAD applications are robust enough to manipulate limited points or polygon models within the CAD environment (e.g., CATIA, AutoCAD, Revit).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] CT, industrial CT, MRI, or micro-CT scanners do not produce point clouds but a set of 2D slices (each termed a "tomogram") which are then 'stacked together' to produce a 3D representation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The laser power used for laser scanning equipment in industrial applications is typically less than 1W.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The power level is usually on the order of 200 mW or less but sometimes more.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 3D data acquisition and object reconstruction can be performed using stereo image pairs.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Stereo photogrammetry or photogrammetry based on a block of overlapped images is the primary approach for 3D mapping and object reconstruction using 2D images.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Close-range photogrammetry has also matured to the level where cameras or digital cameras can be used to capture the close-look images of objects, e.g., buildings, and reconstruct them using the very same theory as the aerial photogrammetry.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] An example of software which could do this is Vexcel FotoG 5.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This software has now been replaced by Vexcel GeoSynth.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Another similar software program is Microsoft Photosynth.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A semi-automatic method for acquiring 3D topologically structured data from 2D aerial stereo images has been presented by Sisi Zlatanova.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The process involves the manual digitizing of a number of points necessary for automatically reconstructing the 3D objects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Each reconstructed object is validated by superimposition of its wire frame graphics in the stereo model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The topologically structured 3D data is stored in a database and are also used for visualization of the objects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Notable software used for 3D data acquisition using 2D images include e.g.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Agisoft Metashape, RealityCapture, and ENSAIS Engineering College TIPHON (Traitement d'Image et PHOtogrammétrie Numérique).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A method for semi-automatic building extraction together with a concept for storing building models alongside terrain and other topographic data in a topographical information system has been developed by Franz Rottensteiner.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] His approach was based on the integration of building parameter estimations into the photogrammetry process applying a hybrid modeling scheme.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Buildings are decomposed into a set of simple primitives that are reconstructed individually and are then combined by Boolean operators.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Multiple images are used in Zhang's approach to surface reconstruction from multiple images.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A central idea is to explore the integration of both 3D stereo data and 2D calibrated images.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This approach is motivated by the fact that only robust and accurate feature points that survived the geometry scrutiny of multiple images are reconstructed in space.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The density insufficiency and the inevitable holes in the stereo data should then be filled in by using information from multiple images.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The idea is thus to first construct small surface patches from stereo points, then to progressively propagate only reliable patches in their neighborhood from images into the whole surface using a best-first strategy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The problem thus reduces to searching for an optimal local surface patch going through a given set of stereo points from images.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Multi-spectral images are also used for 3D building detection.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The first and last pulse data and the normalized difference vegetation index are used in the process.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] New measurement techniques are also employed to obtain measurements of and between objects from single images by using the projection, or the shadow as well as their combination.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This technology is gaining attention given its fast processing time, and far lower cost than stereo measurements.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 3D scanning technology has been used to scan space rocks for the European Space Agency.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are used by the entertainment industry to create digital 3D models for movies, video games and leisure purposes.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] They are heavily utilized in virtual cinematography.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In cases where a real-world equivalent of a model exists, it is much faster to scan the real-world object than to manually create a model using 3D modeling software.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Frequently, artists sculpt physical models of what they want and scan them into digital form rather than directly creating digital models on a computer.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are evolving for the use of cameras to represent 3D objects in an accurate manner.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Companies are emerging since 2010 that create 3D portraits of people (3D figurines or 3D selfie).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 3D laser scanning is used by the law enforcement agencies around the world.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Reverse engineering of a mechanical component requires a precise digital model of the objects to be reproduced.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Rather than a set of points a precise digital model can be represented by a polygon mesh, a set of flat or curved NURBS surfaces, or ideally for mechanical components, a CAD solid model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A 3D scanner can be used to digitise free-form or gradually changing shaped components as well as prismatic geometries whereas a coordinate measuring machine is usually used only to determine simple dimensions of a highly prismatic model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These data points are then processed to create a usable digital model, usually using specialized reverse engineering software.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Land or buildings can be scanned into a 3D model, which allows buyers to tour and inspect the property remotely, anywhere, without having to be present at the property.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] There is already at least one company providing 3D scanned virtual real estate tours.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A typical virtual tour Archived 2017-04-27 at the Wayback Machine would consist of dollhouse view, inside view, as well as a floor plan.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The environment at a place of interest can be captured and converted into a 3D model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This model can then be explored by the public, either through a VR interface or a traditional "2D" interface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This allows the user to explore locations which are inconvenient for travel.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A group of history students at Vancouver iTech Preparatory Middle School created a Virtual Museum by 3D Scanning more than 100 artifacts.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] There have been many research projects undertaken via the scanning of historical sites and artifacts both for documentation and analysis purposes.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The resulting models can be used for a variety of different analytical approaches.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The combined use of 3D scanning and 3D printing technologies allows the replication of real objects without the use of traditional plaster casting techniques, that in many cases can be too invasive for being performed on precious or delicate cultural heritage artifacts.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In an example of a typical application scenario, a gargoyle model was digitally acquired using a 3D scanner and the produced 3D data was processed using MeshLab.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The resulting digital 3D model was fed to a rapid prototyping machine to create a real resin replica of the original object.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] More recently, smartphone-based LiDAR apps have enabled on-site capture of cultural heritage objects; for example, a 1,500-year-old Buddhist stone relief was scanned using a LiDAR-equipped iPhone and the CapCam app, producing a high-density mesh suitable for 3D printing a physical replica.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In 1999, two different research groups started scanning Michelangelo's statues.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Stanford University with a group led by Marc Levoy used a custom laser triangulation scanner built by Cyberware to scan Michelangelo's statues in Florence, notably the David, the Prigioni and the four statues in The Medici Chapel.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The scans produced a data point density of one sample per 0.25 mm, detailed enough to see Michelangelo's chisel marks.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These detailed scans produced a large amount of data (up to 32 gigabytes) and processing the data from his scans took 5 months.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Approximately in the same period a research group from IBM, led by H.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Bernardini scanned the Pietà of Florence acquiring both geometric and color details.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The digital model, result of the Stanford scanning campaign, was thoroughly used in the 2004 subsequent restoration of the statue.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In 2002, David Luebke, et al. scanned Thomas Jefferson's Monticello.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A commercial time of flight laser scanner, the DeltaSphere 3000, was used.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The scanner data was later combined with color data from digital photographs to create the Virtual Monticello, and the Jefferson's Cabinet exhibits in the New Orleans Museum of Art in 2003.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The Virtual Monticello exhibit simulated a window looking into Jefferson's Library.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The exhibit consisted of a rear projection display on a wall and a pair of stereo glasses for the viewer.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The glasses, combined with polarised projectors, provided a 3D effect.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Position tracking hardware on the glasses allowed the display to adapt as the viewer moves around, creating the illusion that the display is actually a hole in the wall looking into Jefferson's Library.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The Jefferson's Cabinet exhibit was a barrier stereogram (essentially a non-active hologram that appears different from different angles) of Jefferson's Cabinet.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The first 3D models of cuneiform tablets were acquired in Germany in 2000.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In 2003 the so-called *Digital Hammurabi project* acquired cuneiform tablets with a laser triangulation scanner using a regular grid pattern having a resolution of 0.025 mm (0.00098 in).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] With the use of high-resolution 3D scanners by the Heidelberg University for tablet acquisition in 2009 the development of the GigaMesh Software Framework began to visualize and extract cuneiform characters from 3D models.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 2.000 3D digitized tablets of the Hilprecht Collection in Jena to create an Open Access benchmark dataset and an annotated collection of 3D models of tablets freely available under CC BY licenses.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A 2009 CyArk 3D scanning project at Uganda's historic Kasubi Tombs, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, using a Leica HDS 4500, produced detailed architectural models of Muzibu Azaala Mpanga, the main building at the complex and tomb of the Kabakas (Kings) of Uganda.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] A fire on March 16, 2010, burned down much of the Muzibu Azaala Mpanga structure, and reconstruction work is likely to lean heavily upon the dataset produced by the 3D scan mission.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In 2005, Gabriele Guidi, et al. scanned the "Plastico di Roma antica", a model of Rome created in the last century.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Neither the triangulation method, nor the time of flight method satisfied the requirements of this project because the item to be scanned was both large and contained small details.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] They found though, that a modulated light scanner was able to provide both the ability to scan an object the size of the model and the accuracy that was needed.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The modulated light scanner was supplemented by a triangulation scanner which was used to scan some parts of the model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The Smithsonian Institution has a project called Smithsonian X 3D notable for the breadth of types of 3D objects they are attempting to scan.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] These include small objects such as insects and flowers, to human sized objects such as Amelia Earhart's Flight Suit to room sized objects such as the Gunboat Philadelphia to historic sites such as Liang Bua in Indonesia.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Also of note the data from these scans is being made available to the public for free and downloadable in several data formats.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] 3D scanners are used to capture the 3D shape of a patient in orthotics and dentistry.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] It gradually supplants tedious plaster cast.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] CAD/CAM software are then used to design and manufacture the orthosis, prosthesis or dental implants.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The chairside systems are designed to facilitate the 3D scanning of a preparation *in vivo* and produce the restoration (such as a Crown, Onlay, Inlay or Veneer).
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Creation of 3D models for anatomy and biology education and cadaver models for educational neurosurgical simulations.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The digitalisation of real-world objects is of vital importance in various application domains.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This method is especially applied in industrial quality assurance to measure the geometric dimension accuracy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Industrial processes such as assembly are complex, highly automated and typically based on CAD (computer-aided design) data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The problem is that the same degree of automation is also required for quality assurance.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] It is, for example, a very complex task to assemble a modern car, since it consists of many parts that must fit together at the very end of the production line.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The optimal performance of this process is guaranteed by quality assurance systems.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Especially the geometry of the metal parts must be checked in order to assure that they have the correct dimensions, fit together and finally work reliably.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Within highly automated processes, the resulting geometric measures are transferred to machines that manufacture the desired objects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Due to mechanical uncertainties and abrasions, the result may differ from its digital nominal.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] In order to automatically capture and evaluate these deviations, the manufactured part must be digitised as well.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] For this purpose, 3D scanners are applied to generate point samples from the object's surface which are finally compared against the nominal data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The process of comparing 3D data against a CAD model is referred to as CAD-Compare, and can be a useful technique for applications such as determining wear patterns on moulds and tooling, determining accuracy of final build, analysing gap and flush, or analysing highly complex sculpted surfaces.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] At present, laser triangulation scanners, structured light and contact scanning are the predominant technologies employed for industrial purposes, with contact scanning remaining the slowest, but overall most accurate option.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Nevertheless, 3D scanning technology offers distinct advantages compared to traditional touch probe measurements.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] White-light or laser scanners accurately digitize objects all around, capturing fine details and freeform surfaces without reference points or spray.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] The entire surface is covered at record speed without the risk of damaging the part.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Graphic comparison charts illustrate geometric deviations of full object level, providing deeper insights into potential causes.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] After the data has been collected, the acquired (and sometimes already processed) data from images or sensors needs to be reconstructed.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] This may be done in the same program or in some cases, the 3D data needs to be exported and imported into another program for further refining, and/or to add additional data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Such additional data could be GPS-location data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] After the reconstruction, the data might be directly implemented into a local (GIS) map or a worldwide map such as Google Earth or Apple Maps.
[src:point-cloud-processing/3d-scanning] Several software packages are used in which the acquired (and sometimes already processed) data from images or sensors is imported.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] The Iterative Closest Point algorithm keeps one point cloud, the reference or target, fixed, while transforming the other, the source, to best match the reference.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] The transformation (combination of translation and rotation) is iteratively estimated in order to minimize an error metric, typically the sum of squared differences between the coordinates of the matched pairs.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] ICP is one of the widely used algorithms in aligning three dimensional models given an initial guess of the rigid transformation required.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] The ICP algorithm was first introduced by Chen and Medioni, and Besl and McKay.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] Inputs: reference and source point clouds, initial estimation of the transformation to align the source to the reference (optional), criteria for stopping the iterations.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] Estimate the combination of rotation and translation using a root mean square point-to-point distance metric minimization technique which will best align each source point to its match found in the previous step.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] This step may also involve weighting points and rejecting outliers prior to alignment.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] Transform the source points using the obtained transformation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] Iterate (re-associate the points, and so on).
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] Zhang proposes a modified *k*-d tree algorithm for efficient closest point computation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] In this work a statistical method based on the distance distribution is used to deal with outliers, occlusion, appearance, and disappearance, which enables subset-subset matching.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] There exist many ICP variants, from which point-to-point and point-to-plane are the most popular.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] The latter usually performs better in structured environments.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] While traditional ICP assumes rigid transformations, non-rigid ICP methods extend the algorithm to handle deformable objects and non-rigid registration scenarios.
[src:point-cloud-processing/iterative-closest-point] These methods incorporate additional constraints and regularization terms to model local deformations while maintaining surface coherence.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] In this view, the viewer flies down to the rainforest canopy and flies through the virtual leaves.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] This visualisation shows an airplane collecting a 50 km swathe of lidar data over the Brazilian rainforest.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] For ground-level features, colours range from deep brown to tan.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Vegetation heights are depicted in shades of green, where dark greens are closest to the ground and light greens are the highest.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar has terrestrial, airborne, and mobile uses.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] It is commonly used to make high-resolution maps, with applications in surveying, geodesy, geomatics, archaeology, geography, geology, geomorphology, seismology, forestry, atmospheric physics, laser guidance, airborne laser swathe mapping (ALSM), and laser altimetry.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] It is used to make digital 3-D representations of areas on the Earth's surface and ocean bottom of the intertidal and near coastal zone by varying the wavelength of light.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] It has also been increasingly used in control and navigation for autonomous cars and for the helicopter *Ingenuity* on its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar has since been used extensively for atmospheric research and meteorology.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar instruments fitted to aircraft and satellites carry out surveying and mapping – a recent example being the U.S.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Geological Survey Experimental Advanced Airborne Research Lidar.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] NASA has identified lidar as a key technology for enabling autonomous precision safe landing of future robotic and crewed lunar-landing vehicles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The essential concept of lidar was originated by E.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Synge in 1930, who envisaged the use of powerful searchlights to probe the atmosphere.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Under the direction of Malcolm Stitch, the Hughes Aircraft Company introduced the first lidar-like system in 1961, shortly after the invention of the laser.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Intended for satellite tracking, this system combined laser-focused imaging with the ability to calculate distances by measuring the time for a signal to return using appropriate sensors and data acquisition electronics.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] It was originally called "Colidar" an acronym for "coherent light detecting and ranging", derived from the term "radar", itself an acronym for "radio detection and ranging".
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] All laser rangefinders, laser altimeters and lidar units are derived from the early colidar systems.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The first practical terrestrial application of a colidar system was the "Colidar Mark II", a large rifle-like laser rangefinder produced in 1963, which had a range of 11 km and an accuracy of 4.5 m, to be used for military targeting.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The first mention of lidar as a stand-alone word in 1963 suggests that it originated as a portmanteau of "light" and "radar": "Eventually the laser may provide an extremely sensitive detector of particular wavelengths from distant objects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Meanwhile, it is being used to study the Moon by 'lidar' (light radar) ..." The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar's first applications were in meteorology, for which the National Center for Atmospheric Research used it to measure clouds and pollution.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The general public became aware of the accuracy and usefulness of lidar systems in 1971 during the Apollo 15 mission, when astronauts used a laser altimeter to map the surface of the Moon.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Although the English language no longer treats "radar" as an acronym, (i.e., uncapitalized), the word "lidar" was capitalized as "LIDAR" or "LiDAR" in some publications beginning in the 1980s.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Various publications refer to lidar as "LIDAR", "LiDAR", "LIDaR", or "Lidar".
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The USGS uses both "LIDAR" and "lidar", sometimes in the same document; the *New York Times* predominantly uses "lidar" for staff-written articles, although contributing news feeds such as Reuters may use Lidar.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar uses ultraviolet, visible, or near infrared light to image objects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] It can target a wide range of materials, including non-metallic objects, rocks, rain, chemical compounds, aerosols, clouds and even single molecules.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] A narrow laser beam can map physical features with very high resolutions; for example, an aircraft can map terrain at 30-centimetre (12 in) resolution or better.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Wavelengths vary to suit the target: from about 10 micrometers (infrared) to approximately 250 nanometers (ultraviolet).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Typically, light is reflected via backscattering, as opposed to pure reflection one might find with a mirror.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Different types of scattering are used for different lidar applications: most commonly Rayleigh scattering, Mie scattering, Raman scattering, and fluorescence.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Suitable combinations of wavelengths can allow remote mapping of atmospheric contents by identifying wavelength-dependent changes in the intensity of the returned signal.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar, although photonic radar more strictly refers to radio-frequency range finding using photonics components.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] where *c* is the speed of light, *d* is the distance between the detector and the object or surface being detected, and *t* is the time spent for the laser light to travel to the object or surface being detected, then travel back to the detector.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The two kinds of lidar detection schemes are "incoherent" or direct energy detection (which principally measures amplitude changes of the reflected light) and coherent detection (best for measuring Doppler shifts, or changes in the phase of the reflected light).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Coherent systems generally use optical heterodyne detection.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] This is more sensitive than direct detection and allows them to operate at much lower power, but requires more complex transceivers.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Both types employ pulse models: either *micropulse* or *high energy*.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Micropulse systems utilize intermittent bursts of energy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] They developed as a result of ever-increasing computer power, combined with advances in laser technology.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] They use considerably less energy in the laser, typically on the order of one microjoule, and are often "eye-safe", meaning they can be used without safety precautions.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] 600–1,000 nm lasers are most common for non-scientific applications.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The maximum power of the laser is limited, or an automatic shut-off system which turns the laser off at specific altitudes is used in order to make it eye-safe for the people on the ground.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] One common alternative, 1,550 nm lasers, are eye-safe at relatively high power levels since this wavelength is strongly absorbed by water and barely reaches the retina, though camera sensors can still get damaged.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] A trade-off though is that current detector technology is less advanced, so these wavelengths are generally used at longer ranges with lower accuracies.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] They are also used for military applications because 1,550 nm is not visible in night vision goggles, unlike the shorter 1,000 nm infrared laser.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Airborne topographic mapping lidars generally use 1,064 nm diode-pumped YAG lasers, while bathymetric (underwater depth research) systems generally use 532 nm frequency-doubled diode pumped YAG lasers because 532 nm penetrates water with much less attenuation than 1,064 nm.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Laser settings include the laser repetition rate (which controls the data collection speed).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Pulse length is generally an attribute of the laser cavity length, the number of passes required through the gain material (YAG, YLF, etc.), and Q-switch (pulsing) speed.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Better target resolution is achieved with shorter pulses, provided the lidar receiver detectors and electronics have sufficient bandwidth.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] A phased array can illuminate any direction by using a microscopic array of individual antennas.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Controlling the timing (phase) of each antenna steers a cohesive signal in a specific direction.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Phased arrays have been used in radar since the 1940s.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] On the order of a million optical antennas are used to see a radiation pattern of a certain size in a certain direction.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] To achieve this the phase of each individual antenna (emitter) are precisely controlled.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] It is very difficult, if possible at all, to use the same technique in a lidar.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The main problems are that all individual emitters must be coherent (technically coming from the same "master" oscillator or laser source), have dimensions about the wavelength of the emitted light (1 micron range) to act as a point source with their phases being controlled with high accuracy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Microelectromechanical mirrors (MEMS) are not entirely solid-state.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] However, their tiny form factor provides many of the same cost benefits.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] A single laser is directed to a single mirror that can be reoriented to view any part of the target field.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] However, MEMS systems generally operate in a single plane (left to right).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] To add a second dimension generally requires a second mirror that moves up and down.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Alternatively, another laser can hit the same mirror from another angle.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] MEMS systems can be disrupted by shock/vibration and may require repeated calibration.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Image development speed is affected by the speed at which they are scanned.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Options to scan the azimuth and elevation include dual oscillating plane mirrors, a combination with a polygon mirror, and a dual axis scanner.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Optic choices affect the angular resolution and range that can be detected.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] A hole mirror or a beam splitter are options to collect a return signal.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Two main photodetector technologies are used in lidar: solid-state photodetectors, such as silicon avalanche photodiodes, or photomultipliers.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The sensitivity of the receiver is another parameter that has to be balanced in a lidar design.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar sensors mounted on mobile platforms such as airplanes or satellites require instrumentation to determine the absolute position and orientation of the sensor.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Such devices generally include a Global Positioning System receiver and an inertial measurement unit (IMU).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar uses active sensors that supply their own illumination source.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The energy source hits objects and the reflected energy is detected and measured by sensors.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Distance to the object is determined by recording the time between transmitted and backscattered pulses and by using the speed of light to calculate the distance traveled.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Flash lidar allows for 3-D imaging because of the camera's ability to emit a larger flash and sense the spatial relationships and dimensions of area of interest with the returned energy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] This allows for more accurate imaging because the captured frames do not need to be stitched together, and the system is not sensitive to platform motion.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] 3-D imaging can be achieved using both scanning and non-scanning systems.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] "3-D gated viewing laser radar" is a non-scanning laser ranging system that applies a pulsed laser and a fast gated camera.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Research has begun for virtual beam steering using digital light processing (DLP) technology.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Imaging lidar can also be performed using arrays of high speed detectors and modulation sensitive detector arrays typically built on single chips using complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) and hybrid CMOS/charge-coupled device (CCD) fabrication techniques.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] In these devices each pixel performs some local processing such as demodulation or gating at high speed, downconverting the signals to video rate so that the array can be read like a camera.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Using this technique many thousands of pixels / channels may be acquired simultaneously.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] High resolution 3-D lidar cameras use homodyne detection with an electronic CCD or CMOS shutter.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] A coherent imaging lidar uses synthetic array heterodyne detection to enable a staring single element receiver to act as though it were an imaging array.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] In 2014, Lincoln Laboratory announced a new imaging chip with more than 16,384 pixels, each able to image a single photon, enabling them to capture a wide area in a single image.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] An earlier generation of the technology with one fourth as many pixels was dispatched by the U.S. military after the January 2010 Haiti earthquake.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] A single pass by a business jet at 3,000 m (10,000 ft) over Port-au-Prince was able to capture instantaneous snapshots of 600 m (2,000 ft) squares of the city at a resolution of 30 cm (1 ft), displaying the precise height of rubble strewn in city streets.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The new system is ten times better, and could produce much larger maps more quickly.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The chip uses indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs), which operates in the infrared spectrum at a relatively long wavelength that allows for higher power and longer ranges.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] In many applications, such as self-driving cars, the new system will lower costs by not requiring a mechanical component to aim the chip.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] InGaAs uses less hazardous wavelengths than conventional silicon detectors, which operate at visual wavelengths.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] New technologies for infrared single-photon counting lidar are advancing rapidly, including arrays and cameras in a variety of semiconductor and superconducting platforms.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar can be oriented to nadir, zenith, or laterally.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] For example, lidar altimeters look down, an atmospheric lidar looks up, and lidar-based collision avoidance systems are side-looking.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar applications can be divided into airborne and terrestrial types.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The two types require scanners with varying specifications based on the data's purpose, the size of the area to be captured, the range of measurement desired, the cost of equipment, and more.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Spaceborne platforms are also possible, see satellite laser altimetry.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar (also *airborne laser scanning*) is when a laser scanner, while attached to an aircraft during flight, creates a 3-D point cloud model of the landscape.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] This is currently the most detailed and accurate method of creating digital elevation models, replacing photogrammetry.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] One major advantage in comparison with photogrammetry is the ability to filter out reflections from vegetation from the point cloud model to create a digital terrain model which represents ground surfaces such as rivers, paths, cultural heritage sites, etc., which are concealed by trees.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Within the category of airborne lidar, there is sometimes a distinction made between high-altitude and low-altitude applications, but the main difference is a reduction in both accuracy and point density of data acquired at higher altitudes.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar can also be used to create bathymetric models in shallow water.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The main constituents of airborne lidar include digital elevation models (DEM) and digital surface models (DSM).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The points and ground points are the vectors of discrete points while DEM and DSM are interpolated raster grids of discrete points.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The process also involves capturing of digital aerial photographs.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] To interpret deep-seated landslides for example, under the cover of vegetation, scarps, tension cracks or tipped trees airborne lidar is used.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar digital elevation models can see through the canopy of forest cover, perform detailed measurements of scarps, erosion and tilting of electric poles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar data is processed using a toolbox called Toolbox for Lidar Data Filtering and Forest Studies (TIFFS) for lidar data filtering and terrain study software.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The data is interpolated to digital terrain models using the software.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The laser is directed at the region to be mapped and each point's height above the ground is calculated by subtracting the original z-coordinate from the corresponding digital terrain model elevation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Based on this height above the ground the non-vegetation data is obtained which may include objects such as buildings, electric power lines, flying birds, insects, etc.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The rest of the points are treated as vegetation and used for modeling and mapping.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Within each of these plots, lidar metrics are calculated by calculating statistics such as mean, standard deviation, skewness, percentiles, quadratic mean, etc.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Multiple commercial lidar systems for unmanned aerial vehicles are currently on the market.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] These platforms can systematically scan large areas, or provide a cheaper alternative to manned aircraft for smaller scanning operations.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The airborne lidar bathymetric technological system involves the measurement of time of flight of a signal from a source to its return to the sensor.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The data acquisition technique involves a sea floor mapping component and a ground truth component that includes video transects and sampling.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] It works using a green spectrum (532 nm) laser beam.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Two beams are projected onto a fast rotating mirror, which creates an array of points.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] One of the beams penetrates the water and also detects the bottom surface of the water under favorable conditions.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Water depth measurable by lidar depends on the clarity of the water and the absorption of the wavelength used.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Water is most transparent to green and blue light, so these will penetrate deepest in clean water.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Blue-green light of 532 nm produced by frequency doubled solid-state IR laser output is the standard for airborne bathymetry.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] This light can penetrate water but pulse strength attenuates exponentially with distance traveled through the water.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Lidar can measure depths from about 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft), with vertical accuracy in the order of 15 cm (6 in).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The surface reflection makes water shallower than about 0.9 m (3 ft) difficult to resolve, and absorption limits the maximum depth.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Turbidity causes scattering and has a significant role in determining the maximum depth that can be resolved in most situations, and dissolved pigments can increase absorption depending on wavelength.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Other reports indicate that water penetration tends to be between two and three times Secchi depth.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Bathymetric lidar is most useful in the 0–10 m (0–33 ft) depth range in coastal mapping.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] On average in fairly clear coastal seawater lidar can penetrate to about 7 m (23 ft), and in turbid water up to about 3 m (10 ft).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] An average value found by Saputra et al, 2021, is for the green laser light to penetrate water about one and a half to two times Secchi depth in Indonesian waters.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Water temperature and salinity have an effect on the refractive index which has a small effect on the depth calculation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The data obtained shows the full extent of the land surface exposed above the sea floor.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] This technique is extremely useful as it will play an important role in the major sea floor mapping program.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The mapping yields onshore topography as well as underwater elevations.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Sea floor reflectance imaging is another solution product from this system which can benefit mapping of underwater habitats.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] This technique has been used for three-dimensional image mapping of California's waters using a hydrographic lidar.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar systems were traditionally able to acquire only a few peak returns, while more recent systems acquire and digitize the entire reflected signal.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Scientists analysed the waveform signal for extracting peak returns using Gaussian decomposition.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Zhuang et al, 2017 used this approach for estimating aboveground biomass.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Handling the huge amounts of full-waveform data is difficult.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Therefore, Gaussian decomposition of the waveforms is effective, since it reduces the data and is supported by existing workflows that support interpretation of 3-D point clouds.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Recent studies investigated voxelisation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The intensities of the waveform samples are inserted into a voxelised space (3-D grayscale image) building up a 3-D representation of the scanned area.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Related metrics and information can then be extracted from that voxelised space.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Structural information can be extracted using 3-D metrics from local areas and there is a case study that used the voxelisation approach for detecting dead standing eucalypt trees in Australia.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Terrestrial applications of lidar (also *terrestrial laser scanning*) happen on the Earth's surface and can be either stationary or mobile.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Stationary terrestrial scanning is most common as a survey method, for example in conventional topography, monitoring, cultural heritage documentation and forensics.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The 3-D point clouds acquired from these types of scanners can be matched with digital images taken of the scanned area from the scanner's location to create realistic looking 3-D models in a relatively short time when compared to other technologies.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Each point in the point cloud is given the colour of the pixel from the image taken at the same location and direction as the laser beam that created the point.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Terrestrial lidar mapping involves a process of occupancy grid map generation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The process involves an array of cells divided into grids which employ a process to store the height values when lidar data falls into the respective grid cell.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] A binary map is then created by applying a particular threshold to the cell values for further processing.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] The next step is to process the radial distance and z-coordinates from each scan to identify which 3-D points correspond to each of the specified grid cell leading to the process of data formation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Mobile lidar (also *mobile laser scanning*) is when two or more scanners are attached to a moving vehicle to collect data along a path.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] These scanners are almost always paired with other kinds of equipment, including GNSS receivers and IMUs.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] One example application is surveying streets, where power lines, exact bridge heights, bordering trees, etc. all need to be taken into account.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] Instead of collecting each of these measurements individually in the field with a tachymeter, a 3-D model from a point cloud can be created where all of the measurements needed can be made, depending on the quality of the data collected.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p01] This eliminates the problem of forgetting to take a measurement, so long as the model is available, reliable and has an appropriate level of accuracy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] There are a wide variety of lidar applications, in addition to the applications listed below, as it is often mentioned in national lidar dataset programs.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Companies are working to cut the cost of lidar sensors, currently anywhere from about US$1,200 to more than $12,000.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lower prices will make lidar more attractive for new markets.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Agricultural robots have been used for a variety of purposes ranging from seed and fertilizer dispersions, sensing techniques as well as crop scouting for the task of weed control.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar can help determine where to apply costly fertilizer.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] It can create a topographical map of the fields and reveal slopes and sun exposure of the farmland.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Researchers at the Agricultural Research Service used this topographical data with the farmland yield results from previous years, to categorize land into zones of high, medium, or low yield.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This indicates where to apply fertilizer to maximize yield.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar is now used to monitor insects in the field.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The use of lidar can detect the movement and behavior of individual flying insects, with identification down to sex and species.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In 2017 a patent application was published on this technology in the United States, Europe, and China.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Another application is crop mapping in orchards and vineyards, to detect foliage growth and the need for pruning or other maintenance, detect variations in fruit production, or count plants.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar is useful in GNSS-denied situations, such as nut and fruit orchards, where foliage causes interference for agriculture equipment that would otherwise utilize a precise GNSS fix.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors can detect and track the relative position of rows, plants, and other markers so that farming equipment can continue operating until a GNSS fix is reestablished.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Controlling weeds requires identifying plant species.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This can be done by using 3-D lidar and machine learning.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar produces plant contours as a "point cloud" with range and reflectance values.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This data is transformed, and features are extracted from it.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] If the species is known, the features are added as new data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The species is labelled and its features are initially stored as an example to identify the species in the real environment.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This method is efficient because it uses a low-resolution lidar and supervised learning.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] It includes an easy-to-compute feature set with common statistical features which are independent of the plant size.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In April 2025, Dallas Fort Worth International Airport announced the deployment of a lidar-based platform for real-time monitoring of passenger and vehicle flows.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar has many uses in archaeology, including planning of field campaigns, mapping features under forest canopy, and overview of broad, continuous features indistinguishable from the ground.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar can produce high-resolution datasets quickly and cheaply.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar-derived products can be easily integrated into a geographic information system (GIS) for analysis and interpretation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar can also help to create high-resolution digital elevation models (DEMs) of archaeological sites that can reveal micro-topography that is otherwise hidden by vegetation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The intensity of the returned lidar signal can be used to detect features buried under flat vegetated surfaces such as fields, especially when mapping using the infrared spectrum.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The presence of these features affects plant growth and thus the amount of infrared light reflected back.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] For example, at Fort Beauséjour – Fort Cumberland National Historic Site, Canada, lidar discovered archaeological features related to the siege of the Fort in 1755.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Features that could not be distinguished on the ground or through aerial photography were identified by overlaying hill shades of the DEM created with artificial illumination from various angles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Another example is work at Caracol by Arlen Chase and his wife Diane Zaino Chase.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar was used to search for the legendary city of La Ciudad Blanca or "City of the Monkey God" in the La Mosquitia region of the Honduran jungle.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] During a seven-day mapping period, evidence was found of man-made structures.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In June 2013, the rediscovery of the city of Mahendraparvata was announced.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In southern New England, lidar was used to reveal stone walls, building foundations, abandoned roads, and other landscape features obscured in aerial photography by the region's dense forest canopy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In Cambodia, lidar data were used by Damian Evans and Roland Fletcher to reveal anthropogenic changes to Angkor landscape.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar revealed that the Purépecha settlement of Angamuco in Michoacán, Mexico had about as many buildings as today's Manhattan; while in 2016, its use in mapping ancient Maya causeways in northern Guatemala, revealed 17 elevated roads linking the ancient city of El Mirador to other sites.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In 2018, archaeologists using lidar discovered more than 60,000 man-made structures in the Maya Biosphere Reserve, a "major breakthrough" that showed the Maya civilization was much larger than previously thought.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In 2024, archaeologists using lidar discovered the Upano Valley sites.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Autonomous vehicles may use lidar for obstacle detection and avoidance to navigate safely through environments.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The introduction of lidar was a pivotal occurrence that was the key enabler behind Stanley, the first autonomous vehicle to successfully complete the DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Point cloud output from the lidar sensor provides the necessary data for robot software to determine where potential obstacles exist in the environment and where the robot is in relation to those potential obstacles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Singapore's *Singapore-MIT Alliance for Research and Technology (SMART)* is actively developing technologies for autonomous lidar vehicles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The very first generations of automotive adaptive cruise control systems used only lidar sensors.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In transportation systems, to ensure vehicle and passenger safety and to develop electronic systems that deliver driver assistance, understanding the vehicle and its surrounding environment is essential.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar systems play an important role in the safety of transportation systems.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Many electronic systems which enhance driver assistance and vehicle safety such as adaptive cruise control (ACC), emergency brake assist, and anti-lock braking system (ABS) depend on the detection of a vehicle's environment to act autonomously or semi-autonomously.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar mapping and estimation achieve this.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Current lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors which split the laser beam.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The upper three beams are used for vehicle and obstacles ahead, and the lower beams are used to detect lane markings and road features.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The major advantage of using lidar is that the spatial structure is obtained and this data can be fused with other sensors such as radar, etc. to get a better picture of the vehicle environment in terms of static and dynamic properties of the objects present in the environment.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Conversely, a significant issue with lidar is the difficulty in reconstructing point cloud data in poor weather conditions.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In heavy rain, for example, the light pulses emitted from the lidar system are partially reflected off of rain droplets which adds noise to the data, called 'echoes'.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Obstacle detection and road environment recognition using lidar, proposed by Kun Zhou et al. not only focuses on object detection and tracking but also recognizes lane marking and road features.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] As mentioned earlier, the lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors that split the laser beam into six beams.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The upper three layers are used to detect the forward objects such as vehicles and roadside objects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The sensor is made of weather-resistant material.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The data detected by lidar are clustered to several segments and tracked by Kalman filter.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Data clustering here is done based on characteristics of each segment based on object model, which distinguish different objects such as vehicles, signboards, etc.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] These characteristics include the dimensions of the object, etc.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The reflectors on the rear edges of vehicles are used to differentiate vehicles from other objects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Object tracking is done using a two-stage Kalman filter considering the stability of tracking and the accelerated motion of objects Lidar reflective intensity data is also used for curb detection by making use of robust regression to deal with occlusions.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Road marking is detected using a modified Otsu method by distinguishing rough and shiny surfaces.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Roadside reflectors that indicate lane border are sometimes hidden due to various reasons.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Therefore, other information is needed to recognize the road border.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The lidar used in this method can measure the reflectivity from the object.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Hence, with this data the road border can also be recognized.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Also, the usage of a sensor with a weather-robust head helps to detect the objects even in bad weather conditions.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Canopy height model before and after a flood is a good example.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar can detect highly detailed canopy height data as well as its road border.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar measurements help identify the spatial structure of the obstacle.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This helps distinguish objects based on size and estimate the impact of driving over it.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar systems provide better range and a large field of view, which helps in detecting obstacles on the curves.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This is one of its major advantages over radar systems, which have a narrower field of view.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The fusion of lidar measurement with different sensors makes the system robust and useful in real-time applications, since lidar-dependent systems cannot estimate the dynamic information about the detected object.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] It has been shown that lidar can be manipulated, such that self-driving cars are tricked into taking evasive action.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar has also found many applications for mapping natural and managed landscapes such as forests, wetlands, and grasslands.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Canopy heights, biomass measurements, and leaf area can all be studied using airborne lidar systems.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Similarly, lidar is also used by many industries, including Energy and Railroad, and the Department of Transportation as a faster way of surveying.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Topographic maps can also be generated readily from lidar, including for recreational use such as in the production of orienteering maps.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been applied to estimate and assess the biodiversity of plants, fungi, and animals.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Using southern bull kelp in New Zealand, coastal lidar mapping data has been compared with population genomic evidence to form hypotheses regarding the occurrence and timing of prehistoric earthquake uplift events.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar systems have also been applied to improve forestry management.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Measurements are used to take inventory in forest plots as well as calculate individual tree heights, crown width and crown diameter.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Other statistical analysis use lidar data to estimate total plot information such as canopy volume, mean, minimum and maximum heights, vegetation cover, biomass, and carbon density.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Aerial lidar was used to map the bush fires in Australia in early 2020.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The data was manipulated to view bare earth, and identify healthy and burned vegetation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] High-resolution digital elevation maps generated by airborne and stationary lidar have led to significant advances in geomorphology (the branch of geoscience concerned with the origin and evolution of the Earth surface topography).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In 2005 the Tour Ronde in the Mont Blanc massif became the first high alpine mountain on which lidar was employed to monitor the increasing occurrence of severe rock-fall over large rock faces allegedly caused by climate change and degradation of permafrost at high altitude.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used in structural geology and geophysics as a combination between airborne lidar and GNSS for the detection and study of faults, for measuring uplift.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The output of the two technologies can produce extremely accurate elevation models for terrain – models that can even measure ground elevation through trees.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This combination was used most famously to find the location of the Seattle Fault in Washington, United States.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This combination also measures uplift at Mount St.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Helens by using data from before and after the 2004 uplift.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar systems monitor glaciers and have the ability to detect subtle amounts of growth or decline.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] A satellite-based system, the NASA ICESat, includes a lidar sub-system for this purpose.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The NASA Airborne Topographic Mapper is also used extensively to monitor glaciers and perform coastal change analysis.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The combination is also used by soil scientists while creating a soil survey.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The detailed terrain modeling allows soil scientists to see slope changes and landform breaks which indicate patterns in soil spatial relationships.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Initially, based on ruby lasers, lidar for meteorological applications was constructed shortly after the invention of the laser and represents one of the first applications of laser technology.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar technology has since expanded vastly in capability and lidar systems are used to perform a range of measurements that include profiling clouds, measuring winds, studying aerosols, and quantifying various atmospheric components.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Atmospheric components can in turn provide useful information including surface pressure (by measuring the absorption of oxygen or nitrogen), greenhouse gas emissions (carbon dioxide and methane), photosynthesis (carbon dioxide), fires (carbon monoxide), and humidity (water vapor).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Atmospheric lidars can be either ground-based, airborne or satellite-based depending on the type of measurement.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] 2. by measuring the scattered reflection off the ground (when the lidar is airborne) or other hard surface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Backscatter from the atmosphere directly gives a measure of clouds and aerosols.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Other derived measurements from backscatter such as winds or cirrus ice crystals require careful selecting of the wavelength and/or polarization detected.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] *Doppler lidar* and *Rayleigh Doppler lidar* are used to measure temperature and wind speed along the beam by measuring the frequency of the backscattered light.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The Doppler broadening of gases in motion allows the determination of properties via the resulting frequency shift.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Scanning lidars, such as NASA's conical-scanning HARLIE, have been used to measure atmospheric wind velocity.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The ESA wind mission *ADM-Aeolus* will be equipped with a Doppler lidar system in order to provide global measurements of vertical wind profiles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] A doppler lidar system was used in the 2008 Summer Olympics to measure wind fields during the yacht competition.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Doppler lidar systems are also now beginning to be successfully applied in the renewable energy sector to acquire wind speed, turbulence, wind veer, and wind shear data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Both pulsed and continuous wave systems are being used.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Pulsed systems use signal timing to obtain vertical distance resolution, whereas continuous wave systems rely on detector focusing.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The term *eolics* has been proposed to describe the collaborative and interdisciplinary study of wind using computational fluid mechanics simulations and Doppler lidar measurements.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The ground reflection of an airborne lidar gives a measure of surface reflectivity (assuming the atmospheric transmittance is well known) at the lidar wavelength, however, the ground reflection is typically used for making absorption measurements of the atmosphere.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] "Differential absorption lidar" (DIAL) measurements utilize two or more closely spaced (less than 1 nm) wavelengths to factor out surface reflectivity as well as other transmission losses, since these factors are relatively insensitive to wavelength.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] When tuned to the appropriate absorption lines of a particular gas, DIAL measurements can be used to determine the concentration (mixing ratio) of that particular gas in the atmosphere.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This is referred to as an *integrated path differential absorption* (IPDA) approach, since it is a measure of the integrated absorption along the entire lidar path.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars can be either pulsed or CW and typically use two or more wavelengths.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars have been used for remote sensing of carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In Japan, differential absorption lidar (DIAL) and Raman lidar technologies are being developed to improve the accuracy of flood forecasting and rainfall prediction.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] A research by several companies, universities, and institutes, led by Kyushu University is conducting work on meteorological sensing and flood-risk modelling under a government program.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In May 2025, EKO Instruments began a field study on Goto Fukue Island, Nagasaki Prefecture, using a Micropulse DIAL lidar system provided by the National Center for Atmospheric Research (NSF NCAR).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The study compares DIAL performance with existing Raman lidar systems.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Ltd. signed a technology license agreement in February 2025 with Montana State University, NSF NCAR, and NASA, covering key DIAL-related patents.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Few military applications are known to be in place and are classified (such as the lidar-based speed measurement of the AGM-129 ACM stealth nuclear cruise missile), but a considerable amount of research is underway in their use for imaging.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Higher resolution systems collect enough detail to identify targets, such as tanks.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Examples of military applications of lidar include the Airborne Laser Mine Detection System (ALMDS) for counter-mine warfare by Areté Associates.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] A NATO report (RTO-TR-SET-098) evaluated the potential technologies to do stand-off detection for the discrimination of biological warfare agents.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The potential technologies evaluated were long-wave infrared (LWIR), differential scattering (DISC), and ultraviolet laser-induced fluorescence (UV-LIF).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Short-range compact spectrometric lidar based on laser-induced fluorescence (LIF) would address the presence of bio-threats in aerosol form over critical indoor, semi-enclosed and outdoor venues such as stadiums, subways, and airports.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This near real-time capability would enable rapid detection of a bioaerosol release and allow for timely implementation of measures to protect occupants and minimize the extent of contamination.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The Long-Range Biological Standoff Detection System (LR-BSDS) was developed for the U.S.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Army to provide the earliest possible standoff warning of a biological attack.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] It is an airborne system carried by helicopter to detect synthetic aerosol clouds containing biological and chemical agents at long range.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The LR-BSDS, with a detection range of 30 km or more, was fielded in June 1997.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Five lidar units produced by the German company Sick AG were used for short range detection on Stanley, the autonomous car that won the 2005 DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] A robotic Boeing AH-6 performed a fully autonomous flight in June 2010, including avoiding obstacles using lidar.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The calculation of ore volumes is accomplished by periodic (monthly) scanning in areas of ore removal, then comparing surface data to the previous scan.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors may also be used for obstacle detection and avoidance for robotic mining vehicles such as in the Komatsu Autonomous Haulage System (AHS) used in Rio Tinto's Mine of the Future.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] A worldwide network of observatories uses lidars to measure the distance to reflectors placed on the Moon, allowing the position of the Moon to be measured with millimeter precision and tests of general relativity to be done.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] MOLA, the Mars Orbiting Laser Altimeter, used a lidar instrument in a Mars-orbiting satellite (the NASA Mars Global Surveyor) to produce a spectacularly precise global topographic survey of the red planet.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Laser altimeters produced global elevation models of Mars, the Moon (Lunar Orbiter Laser Altimeter (LOLA)), and Mercury (Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA), NEAR–Shoemaker Laser Rangefinder (NLR)).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Future missions will also include laser altimeter experiments such as the Ganymede Laser Altimeter (GALA) as part of the Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In September, 2008, the NASA *Phoenix* lander used lidar to detect snow in the atmosphere of Mars.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In atmospheric physics, lidar is used as a remote detection instrument to measure densities of certain constituents of the middle and upper atmosphere, such as potassium, sodium, or molecular nitrogen and oxygen.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] These measurements can be used to calculate temperatures.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to measure wind speed and to provide information about vertical distribution of the aerosol particles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] At the JET nuclear fusion research facility in the UK near Abingdon, Oxfordshire, lidar Thomson scattering is used to determine electron density and temperature profiles of the plasma.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar has been widely used in rock mechanics for rock mass characterization and slope change detection.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Some important geomechanical properties from the rock mass can be extracted from the 3-D point clouds obtained by means of the lidar.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Some of these properties have been used to assess the geomechanical quality of the rock mass through the RMR index.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Moreover, as the orientations of discontinuities can be extracted using the existing methodologies, it is possible to assess the geomechanical quality of a rock slope through the SMR index.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In addition to this, the comparison of different 3-D point clouds from a slope acquired at different times allows researchers to study the changes produced on the scene during this time interval as a result of rockfalls or any other landsliding processes.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] THOR is a laser designed toward measuring Earth's atmospheric conditions.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The laser enters a cloud cover and measures the thickness of the return halo.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The sensor has a fiber optic aperture with a width of 7+1⁄2 inches (19 cm) that is used to measure the return light.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar technology is being used in robotics for the perception of the environment as well as object classification.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The ability of lidar technology to provide three-dimensional elevation maps of the terrain, high precision distance to the ground, and approach velocity can enable safe landing of robotic and crewed vehicles with a high degree of precision.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar is also widely used in robotics for simultaneous localization and mapping and is well-integrated into robot simulators.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Refer to the Military section above for further examples.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar is increasingly being utilized for rangefinding and orbital element calculation of relative velocity in proximity operations and stationkeeping of spacecraft.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been used for atmospheric studies from space.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Short pulses of laser light beamed from a spacecraft can reflect off tiny particles in the atmosphere and back to a telescope aligned with the spacecraft laser.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] By precisely timing the lidar echo, and by measuring how much laser light is received by the telescope, scientists can accurately determine the location, distribution and nature of the particles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The result is a revolutionary new tool for studying constituents in the atmosphere, from cloud droplets to industrial pollutants, which are difficult to detect by other means.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Laser altimetry is used to make digital elevation maps of planets, including the Mars Orbital Laser Altimeter (MOLA) mapping of Mars, the Lunar Orbital Laser Altimeter (LOLA) and Lunar Altimeter (LALT) mapping of the Moon, and the Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA) mapping of Mercury.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] It is also used to help navigate the helicopter *Ingenuity* in its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar sensors are used by companies in the remote sensing field.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] They can be used to create a DTM (digital terrain model) or DEM (digital elevation model); this is quite a common practice for larger areas as a plane can acquire 3–4 km (2–2+1⁄2 mi) wide swaths in a single flyover.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Greater vertical accuracy of below 50 mm (2 in) can be achieved with a lower flyover, even in forests, where it is able to give the height of the canopy as well as the ground elevation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Typically, a GNSS receiver configured over a georeferenced control point is needed to link the data in with the WGS (World Geodetic System).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar is also in use in hydrographic surveying.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Depending upon the clarity of the water lidar can measure depths from 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft) with a vertical accuracy of 15 cm (6 in) and horizontal accuracy of 2.5 m (8 ft).
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in the railroad industry to generate asset health reports for asset management and by departments of transportation to assess their road conditions.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] CivilMaps.com is a leading company in the field.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in adaptive cruise control (ACC) systems for automobiles.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Systems such as those by Siemens, Hella, Ouster and Cepton use a lidar device mounted on the front of the vehicle, such as the bumper, to monitor the distance between the vehicle and any vehicle in front of it.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In the event where the vehicle in front slows down or is too close, the ACC applies the brakes to slow the vehicle.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] When the road ahead is clear, the ACC allows the vehicle to accelerate to a speed preset by the driver.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] A lidar-based device, the Ceilometer, is used at airports worldwide to measure the height of clouds on runway approach paths.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar can be used to increase the energy output from wind farms by accurately measuring wind speeds and wind turbulence.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Experimental lidar systems can be mounted on the nacelle of a wind turbine or integrated into the rotating spinner to measure oncoming horizontal winds, winds in the wake of the wind turbine, and proactively adjust blades to protect components and increase power.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used to characterise the incident wind resource for comparison with wind turbine power production to verify the performance of the wind turbine by measuring the wind turbine's power curve.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Wind farm optimization can be considered a topic in *applied eolics*.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Another aspect of lidar in wind related industry is to use computational fluid dynamics over lidar-scanned surfaces in order to assess the wind potential, which can be used for optimal wind farm placement.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to assist planners and developers in optimizing solar photovoltaic systems at the city level by determining appropriate roof tops and for determining shading losses.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Recent airborne laser scanning efforts have focused on ways to estimate the amount of solar light hitting vertical building facades, or by incorporating more detailed shading losses by considering the influence from vegetation and larger surrounding terrain.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The 2017 exploration game *Scanner Sombre*, by Introversion Software, uses lidar as a fundamental game mechanic.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In *Build the Earth*, lidar is used to create accurate renders of terrain in *Minecraft* to account for any errors (mainly regarding elevation) in the default generation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The process of rendering terrain into Build the Earth is limited by the amount of data available in region as well as the speed it takes to convert the file into block data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Lidar technology enhances physical security by providing precise, privacy-compliant threat detection for applications such as perimeter protection, building facades, and critical infrastructure monitoring.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] These systems utilize laser-based sensors to create high-density point clouds that function reliably in challenging environmental conditions, including rain, snow, and complete darkness.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] A key advantage of modern systems is the use of 3D lidar, which creates precise volumetric detection zones capturing height, width, and depth, allowing for the accurate classification of object size and movement speed.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The video for the 2007 song "House of Cards" by Radiohead was believed to be the first use of real-time 3-D laser scanning to record a music video.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The range data in the video is not completely from a lidar, as structured light scanning is also used.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In 2020, Apple introduced the fourth generation of iPad Pro with a lidar sensor integrated into the rear camera module, especially developed for augmented reality (AR) experiences.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The feature was later included in the iPhone 12 Pro lineup and subsequent Pro models.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] On Apple devices, lidar empowers portrait mode pictures with night mode, quickens auto focus and improves accuracy in the Measure app.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In 2022, *Wheel of Fortune* started using lidar technology to track when Vanna White moves her hand over the puzzle board to reveal letters.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The first episode to have this technology was in the season 40 premiere.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In flash lidar, the entire field of view is illuminated with a wide diverging laser beam in a single pulse.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This is in contrast to conventional scanning lidar, which uses a collimated laser beam that illuminates a single point at a time, and the beam is raster scanned to illuminate the field of view point-by-point.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] This illumination method requires a different detection scheme as well.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In both scanning and flash lidar, a time-of-flight camera is used to collect information about both the 3-D location and intensity of the light incident on it in every frame.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] However, in scanning lidar, this camera contains only a point sensor, while in flash lidar, the camera contains either a 1-D or a 2-D sensor array, each pixel of which collects 3-D location and intensity information.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] In both cases, the depth information is collected using the time of flight of the laser pulse (i.e., the time it takes each laser pulse to hit the target and return to the sensor), which requires the pulsing of the laser and acquisition by the camera to be synchronized.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The result is a camera that takes pictures of distance, instead of colors.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Flash lidar is especially advantageous when compared to scanning lidar, when the camera, scene, or both are moving, since the entire scene is illuminated at the same time.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] With scanning lidar, motion can cause "jitter" from the lapse in time as the laser rasters over the scene.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] As with all forms of lidar, the onboard source of illumination makes flash lidar an active sensor.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The signal that is returned is processed by embedded algorithms to produce a nearly instantaneous 3-D rendering of objects and terrain features within the field of view of the sensor.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The laser pulse repetition frequency is sufficient for generating 3-D videos with high resolution and accuracy.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The high frame rate of the sensor makes it a useful tool for a variety of applications that benefit from real-time visualization, such as highly precise remote landing operations.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] By immediately returning a 3-D elevation mesh of target landscapes, a flash sensor can be used to identify optimal landing zones in autonomous spacecraft landing scenarios.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Seeing at a distance requires a powerful burst of light.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] The power is limited to levels that do not damage human retinas.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] However, low-cost silicon imagers do not read light in the eye-safe spectrum.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Instead, gallium-arsenide imagers are required, which can boost costs to $200,000.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Gallium-arsenide is the same compound used to produce high-cost, high-efficiency solar panels usually used in space applications.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] Computer stereo vision has shown promise as an alternative to lidar for close-range applications.
[src:point-cloud-processing/lidar-p02] It is significantly more cost effective when appropriate.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The algorithm was developed by William E.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Cline as a result of their research for General Electric.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] At General Electric they worked on a way to efficiently visualize data from CT and MRI devices.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The premise of the algorithm is to divide the input volume into a discrete set of cubes.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] By assuming linear reconstruction filtering, each cube, which contains a piece of a given isosurface, can easily be identified because the sample values at the cube vertices must span the target isosurface value.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] For each cube containing a section of the isosurface, a triangular mesh that approximates the behavior of the trilinear interpolant in the interior cube is generated.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The first published version of the algorithm exploited rotational and reflective symmetry and also sign changes to build the table with 15 unique cases.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] However, due to the existence of ambiguities in the trilinear interpolant behavior in the cube faces and interior, the meshes extracted by the Marching Cubes presented discontinuities and topological issues.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Given a cube of the grid, a face ambiguity occurs when its face vertices have alternating signs.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] That is, the vertices of one diagonal on this face are positive and the vertices on the other are negative.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Observe that in this case, the signs of the face vertices are insufficient to determine the correct way to triangulate the isosurface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Similarly, an interior ambiguity occurs when the signs of the cube vertices are insufficient to determine the correct surface triangulation, i.e., when multiple triangulations are possible for the same cube configuration.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The popularity of the Marching Cubes and its widespread adoption resulted in several improvements in the algorithm to deal with the ambiguities and to correctly track the behavior of the interpolant.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Durst in 1988 was the first to note that the triangulation table proposed by Lorensen and Cline was incomplete, and that certain Marching Cubes cases allow multiple triangulations.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Durst's 'additional reference' was to an earlier, more efficient (see de Araujo) isosurface polygonization algorithm by Wyvill, Wyvill and McPheeters.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Later, Nielson and Hamann in 1991 observed the existence of ambiguities in the interpolant behavior on the face of the cube.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] They proposed a test called Asymptotic Decider to correctly track the interpolant on the faces of the cube.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] In fact, as observed by Natarajan in 1994, this ambiguity problem also occurs inside the cube.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] In his work, the author proposed a disambiguation test based on the interpolant critical points, and added four new cases to the Marching Cubes triangulation table (subcases of the cases 3, 4, 6 and 7).
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] At this point, even with all the improvements proposed to the algorithm and its triangulation table, the meshes generated by the Marching Cubes still had topological incoherencies.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The Marching Cubes 33, proposed by Chernyaev in 1995, is one of the first isosurface extraction algorithms intended to preserve the topology of the trilinear interpolant.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] In his work, Chernyaev extends to 33 the number of cases in the triangulation lookup table.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] He then proposes a different approach to solve the interior ambiguities, which is based on the Asymptotic Decider.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Later, in 2003, Nielson proved that Chernyaev's lookup table is complete and can represent all the possible behaviors of the trilinear interpolant, and Lewiner et al. proposed an implementation to the algorithm.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Also in 2003 Lopes and Brodlie extended the tests proposed by Natarajan.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] In 2013, Custodio et al. noted and corrected algorithmic inaccuracies that compromised the topological correctness of the mesh generated by the Marching Cubes 33 algorithm proposed by Chernyaev.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The algorithm proceeds through the scalar field, taking eight neighbor locations at a time (thus forming an imaginary cube), then determining the polygon(s) needed to represent the part of the isosurface that passes through this cube.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The individual polygons are then fused into the desired surface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] This is done by creating an index to a precalculated array of 256 possible polygon configurations (28=256) within the cube, by treating each of the 8 scalar values as a bit in an 8-bit integer.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] If the scalar's value is higher than the iso-value (i.e., it is inside the surface) then the appropriate bit is set to one, while if it is lower (outside), it is set to zero.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The final value, after all eight scalars are checked, is the actual index to the polygon indices array.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Finally each vertex of the generated polygons is placed on the appropriate position along the cube's edge by linearly interpolating the two scalar values that are connected by that edge.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The gradient of the scalar field at each grid point is also the normal vector of a hypothetical isosurface passing from that point.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Therefore, these normals may be interpolated along the edges of each cube to find the normals of the generated vertices which are essential for shading the resulting mesh with some illumination model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] An implementation of the marching cubes algorithm was patented as United States Patent 4,710,876.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] Another similar algorithm was developed, called marching tetrahedra, in order to circumvent the patent as well as solve a minor ambiguity problem of marching cubes with some cube configurations.
[src:point-cloud-processing/marching-cubes] The patent expired in 2005, and it is now legal for the graphics community to use it without royalties since more than the 20 years have passed from its issue date (December 1, 1987).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **Point Cloud Library** (**PCL**) is an open-source library of algorithms for point cloud processing tasks and 3D geometry processing, such as occur in three-dimensional computer vision.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The library contains algorithms for filtering, feature estimation, surface reconstruction, 3D registration, model fitting, object recognition, and segmentation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Each module is implemented as a smaller library that can be compiled separately (for example, libpcl_filters, libpcl_features, libpcl_surface, ...).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] PCL has its own data format for storing point clouds - **PCD** (Point Cloud Data), but also allows datasets to be loaded and saved in many other formats.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] It is written in C++ and released under the BSD license.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] PCL requires several third-party libraries to function, which must be installed.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Most mathematical operations are implemented using the Eigen library.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The visualization module for 3D point clouds is based on VTK.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Boost is used for shared pointers and the FLANN library for quick k-nearest neighbor search.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Additional libraries such as Qhull, OpenNI, or Qt are optional and extend PCL with additional features.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] PCL is cross-platform software that runs on the most commonly used operating systems: Linux, Windows, macOS and Android.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The library is fully integrated with the Robot Operating System (ROS) and provides support for OpenMP and Intel Threading Building Blocks (TBB) libraries for multi-core parallelism.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The library is constantly updated and expanded, and its use in various industries is constantly growing.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] For example, PCL participated in the Google Summer of Code 2020 initiative with three projects.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] One was the extension of PCL for use with Python using Pybind11.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] A large number of examples and tutorials are available on the PCL website, either as C++ source files or as tutorials with a detailed description and explanation of the individual steps.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] PCL requires for its installation several third-party libraries, which are listed below.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Some libraries are optional and extend PCL with additional features.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The PCL library is built with the CMake build system (http://www.cmake.org/) at least in version 3.5.0.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **PCD** (**Point Cloud Data**) is a file format for storing 3D point cloud data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] It was created because existing formats did not support some of the features provided by the PCL library.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] PCD is the primary data format in PCL, but the library also offers the ability to save and load data in other formats (such as PLY, IFS, VTK, STL, OBJ, X3D).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] However, these other formats do not have the flexibility and speed of PCD files.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] One of the PCD advantages is the ability to store and process organized point cloud datasets.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Another is very fast saving and loading of points that are stored in binary form.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The PCD version is specified with the numbers 0.x (e.g., 0.5, 0.6, etc.) in the header of each file.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The main difference compared to version 0.6 is that a new header - VIEWPOINT has been added.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] It specifies the information about the orientation of the sensor relative to the dataset.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The PCD file is divided into two parts - **header** and **data**.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The header has a precisely defined format and contains the necessary information about the point cloud data that are stored in it.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The header must be encoded in ASCII, however, the data can be stored in ASCII or binary format.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Thanks to the fact that the ASCII format is more human readable, it can be opened in standard software tools and easily edited.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] In version 0.7 the *version* of the PCD file is at the beginning of the header, followed by the *name*, *size*, and *type* of each dimension of the stored data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] It also shows a number of points (*height***width*) in the whole cloud and information about whether the point cloud dataset is organized or unorganized.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The *data* type specifies in which format the point cloud data are stored (ASCII or binary).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The header is followed by a set of points.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Each point can be stored on a separate line (unorganized point-cloud) or they are stored in an image-like organized structure (organized point-cloud).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] More detailed information about header entries can be found in documentation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The order of header entries is important!
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The development of the Point Cloud Library started in March 2010 at Willow Garage.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The project initially resided on a sub domain of Willow Garage then moved to a new website www.pointclouds.org in March 2011.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] PCL's first official release (Version 1.0) was released two months later in May 2011.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] PCL is divided into several smaller code libraries that can be compiled separately.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Some of the most important modules and their functions are described below.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] When scanning a 3D point cloud, errors and various deviations can occur, which causes noise in the data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] This complicates the estimation of some local point cloud characteristics, such as surface normals.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] These inaccuracies can lead to significant errors in further processing and it is therefore advisable to remove them with a suitable filter.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_filters** library provides several useful filters for removing outliers and noise and also downsampling the data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Some of them use simple criteria to trim points, others use statistical analysis.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_features** library contains algorithms and data structures for 3D feature estimation.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Mostly used local geometric features are the point normal and underlying surface's estimated curvature.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The features describe geometrical patterns at a certain point based on selected k-neighborhood (data space selected around the point).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The neighborhood can be selected by determining a fixed number of points in the closest area or defining a radius of a sphere around the point.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] One of the easiest implemented methods for estimating the surface normal is an analysis of the eigenvectors and eigenvalues of a covariance matrix created from the neighborhood of the point.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Point Feature Histograms (or faster FPFH) descriptors are an advanced feature representation and depend on normal estimations at each point.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] It generalizes the mean curvature around the point using a multidimensional histogram of values.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Some of other descriptors in the library are Viewpoint Feature Histogram (VFH) descriptor, NARF descriptors, Moment of inertia and eccentricity based descriptors, Globally Aligned Spatial Distribution (GASD) descriptors, and more.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_segmentation** library contains algorithms for segmenting a point cloud into different clusters.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Clustering is often used to divide the cloud into individual parts, that can be further processed.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_visualization** library is used to quickly and easily visualize 3D point cloud data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The package makes use of the VTK library for 3D rendering of clouds and range images.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Registration is the problem of aligning various point cloud datasets acquired from different views into a single point cloud model.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_registration** library implements number of point cloud registration algorithms for both organized and unorganized datasets.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The task is to identify the corresponding points between the data sets and find a transformation that minimizes their distance.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The iterative closest point algorithm minimizes the distances between the points of two pointclouds.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] It can be used for determining if one PointCloud is just a rigid transformation of another.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Normal Distributions Transform (NDT) is a registration algorithm that can be used to determine a rigid transformation between two point clouds that have over 100,000 points.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The ***sample_consensus*** library holds SAmple Consensus (SAC) methods like RANSAC and models to detect specific objects in point clouds.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Some of the models implemented in this library include plane models that are often used to detect interior surfaces such as walls and floors.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Next models are the lines, 2D and 3D circles in a plane, sphere, cylinder, cone, a model for determining a line parallel with a given axis, a model for determining a plane perpendicular to a user-specified axis, plane parallel to a user-specified axis, etc.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] These can be used to detect objects with common geometric structures (e.g., fitting a cylinder model to a mug).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Several algorithms for surface reconstruction of 3D point clouds are implemented in the **pcl_surface** library.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] There are several ways to reconstruct the surface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] One of the most commonly used is meshing, and the PCL library has two algorithms: very fast triangulation of original points and slower networking, which also smooths and fills holes.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] If the cloud is noisy, it is advisable to use surface smoothing using one of the implemented algorithms.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The Moving Least Squares (MLS) surface reconstruction method is a resampling algorithm that can reconstruct missing parts of a surface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Thanks to higher order polynomial interpolations between surrounding data points, MLS can correct and smooth out small errors caused by scanning.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Greedy Projection Triangulation implements an algorithm for fast surface triangulation on an unordered PointCloud with normals.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The result is a triangle mesh that is created by projecting the local neighborhood of a point along the normal of the point.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] It works best if the surface is locally smooth and there are smooth transitions between areas with different point densities.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Many parameters can be set that are taken into account when connecting points (how many neighbors are searched, the maximum distance for a point, minimum and maximum angle of a triangle).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The library also implements functions for creating a concave or convex hull polygon for a plane model, Grid projection surface reconstruction algorithm, marching cubes, ear clipping triangulation algorithm, Poisson surface reconstruction algorithm, etc.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **io_library** allows you to load and save point clouds to files, as well as capture clouds from various devices.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] It includes functions that allow you to concatenate the points of two different point clouds with the same type and number of fields.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The library can also concatenate fields (e.g., dimensions) of two different point clouds with same number of points.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Starting with **PCL 1.0** the library offers a new generic grabber interface that provides easy access to different devices and file formats.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The first devices supported for data collection were OpenNI compatible cameras (tested with *Primesense Reference Design*, *Microsoft Kinect* and *Asus Xtion Pro cameras*).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] As of **PCL 1.7**, point cloud data can be also obtained from the Velodyne High Definition LiDAR (HDL) system, which produces 360 degree point clouds.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] PCL supports both the original *HDL-64e* and *HDL-32e*.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] There is also a new driver for Dinast Cameras (tested with *IPA-1110*, *Cyclopes II* and *IPA-1002 ng T-Less NG*).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] **PCL 1.8** brings support for IDS-Imaging Ensenso cameras, DepthSense cameras (e.g.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] *Creative Senz3D*, *DepthSense DS325*), and davidSDK scanners.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_kdtree** library provides the kd-tree data-structure for organizing a set of points in a space with k dimensions.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Used to find the K nearest neighbors (using FLANN) of a specific point or location.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_octree** library implements the octree hierarchical tree data structure for point cloud data.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The library provides nearest neighbor search algorithms, such as “Neighbors within Voxel Search”, “K Nearest Neighbor Search” and “Neighbors within Radius Search”.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] There are also several octree types that differ by their leaf node's properties.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] Each leaf node can hold a single point or a list of point indices, or it does not store any point information.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The library can be also used for detection of spatial changes between multiple unorganized point clouds by recursive comparison of octet tree structures.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_search** library implements methods for searching for nearest neighbors using different data structures, that can be found in other modules, such as KdTree, Octree, or specialized search for organized datasets.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **range_image** library contains two classes for representing and working with range images whose pixel values represent a distance from the sensor.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The range image can be converted to a point cloud if the sensor position is specified or the borders can be extracted from it.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_keypoints** library contains implementations of point cloud keypoint detection algorithms (AGAST corner point detector, Harris detector, BRISK detector, etc.).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The **pcl_common** library contains the core data structures for point cloud, types for point representation, surface normals, RGB color values, etc.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] There are also implemented useful methods for computing distances, mean values and covariance, geometric transformations, and more.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud-library] The common library is mainly used by other PCL modules.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] A **point cloud** is a discrete set of data points in space.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] The points may represent a 3D shape or object.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Each point position has its set of Cartesian coordinates (X, Y, Z).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Points may contain data other than position such as RGB colors, normals, timestamps and others.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Point clouds are generally produced by 3D scanners or by photogrammetry software, which measure many points on the external surfaces of objects around them.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] When scanning a scene in real world using Lidar, the captured point clouds contain snippets of the scene, which requires alignment to generate a full map of the scanned environment.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Point clouds are often aligned with 3D models or with other point clouds, a process termed point set registration.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] The Iterative closest point (ICP) algorithm can be used to align two point clouds that have an overlap between them, and are separated by a rigid transform.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Point clouds with elastic transforms can also be aligned by using a non-rigid variant of the ICP (NICP).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] With advancements in machine learning in recent years, point cloud registration may also be done using end-to-end neural networks.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] For industrial metrology or inspection using industrial computed tomography, the point cloud of a manufactured part can be aligned to an existing model and compared to check for differences.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Geometric dimensions and tolerances can also be extracted directly from the point cloud.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] While point clouds can be directly rendered and inspected, point clouds are often converted to polygon mesh or triangle mesh models, non-uniform rational B-spline (NURBS) surface models, or CAD models through a process commonly referred to as surface reconstruction.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] There are many techniques for converting a point cloud to a 3D surface.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] In geographic information systems, point clouds are one of the sources used to make digital elevation model of the terrain.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] They are also used to generate 3D models of urban environments.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Drones are often used to collect a series of RGB images which can be later processed on a computer vision algorithm platform such as on AgiSoft Photoscan, Pix4D, DroneDeploy or Hammer Missions to create RGB point clouds from where distances and volumetric estimations can be made.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Point clouds can also be used to represent volumetric data, as is sometimes done in medical imaging.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Using point clouds, multi-sampling and data compression can be achieved.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] MPEG began standardizing point cloud compression (PCC) with a Call for Proposal (CfP) in 2017.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Three categories of point clouds were identified: category 1 for static point clouds, category 2 for dynamic point clouds, and category 3 for Lidar sequences (dynamically acquired point clouds).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Two technologies were finally defined: G-PCC (Geometry-based PCC, ISO/IEC 23090 part 9) for category 1 and category 3; and V-PCC (Video-based PCC, ISO/IEC 23090 part 5) for category 2.
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] The first test models were developed in October 2017, one for G-PCC (TMC13) and another one for V-PCC (TMC2).
[src:point-cloud-processing/point-cloud] Since then, the two test models have evolved through technical contributions and collaboration, and the first version of the PCC standard specifications was expected to be finalized in 2020 as part of the ISO/IEC 23090 series on the coded representation of immersive media content.
